{"title_page": "Ice Cream Cake (EP)", "text_new": "{{about|the Red Velvet EP|the dessert|Ice cream cake}}\n{{short description|Extended play by Red Velvet}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Ice Cream Cake\n| type         = ep\n| artist       = [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]\n| cover        = Ice_Cream_Cake_(EP).jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = Digital and Ice Cream Cake version cover\n| released     = March 17, 2015<ref name=\"iTunes Store\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/album/id977068452 |title=The 1st Mini Album 'Ice Cream Cake' - EP by Red Velvet on iTunes |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] |accessdate=November 4, 2015}}</ref>\n| recorded     = 2014\u20132015\n| studio       = S.M. Studios\n| genre        = * [[Pop]]\n* [[Dance-pop]]\n* [[Drum and bass]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Neo soul]]\n* [[Synth-pop]]\n| length       = 21:22\n| language     = [[Korean language|Korean]]\n| label        = [[SM Entertainment]]\n| producer     = * [[Lee Soo-man]] ([[Executive producer|exec.]])\n* [[Hayley Aitken]]\n* Trinity Music\n* [[Deekay|Daniel \"Obi\" Klein]]\n* [[Charli Taft]]\n* [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]]\n* [[Teddy Riley]]\n* [[Cha Cha Malone]]\n* MonoTree\n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = [[The Red (album)|The Red]]\n| next_year    = 2015\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Ice Cream Cake\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = [[Automatic (Red Velvet song)|Automatic]]\n | single1date = March 14, 2015\n | single2     = [[Ice Cream Cake (Red Velvet song)|Ice Cream Cake]]\n | single2date = March 16, 2015\n}}\n{{External music video|type= EP|{{YouTube|px2Q47O0_eE|\"Automatic\"}}<br />{{YouTube|glXgSSOKlls|\"Ice Cream Cake\"}}}}\n}}\n\n'''''Ice Cream Cake''''' is the debut [[extended play]] by South Korean [[girl group]] [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]. It was released digitally on March 17, 2015,<ref name=\"iTunes Store\" /> and physically on March 18<ref name=\"Mwave1\">{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/89232/red-velvet-to-pre-release-ice-cream-cake-online-a-day-ahead-of-album-release|title=Red Velvet to Pre-release \u2032Ice Cream Cake\u2032 Online A Day Ahead of Album Release|last=Hong|first=Grace Danbi|date=March 13, 2015|website=enewsWorld|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202832/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/89232/red-velvet-to-pre-release-ice-cream-cake-online-a-day-ahead-of-album-release|archive-date=March 3, 2016|accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref> by [[SM Entertainment]] and distributed by [[KT Music]], marking the group's first proper release since their initial debut in August 2014 and their first release as a quintet with the addition of the group's fifth member, [[Yeri (singer)|Yeri]]. The extended play was released in two physical versions, named after the two singles and contained six tracks which introduced both the group's [[Red Velvet (group)#Artistry|\"Red\" and \"Velvet\" sonic concept]]. The duality was further demonstrated by its two [[Single (music)|singles]] (marketed as double title tracks), \"[[Automatic (Red Velvet song)|Automatic]]\" and \"[[Ice Cream Cake (Red Velvet song)|Ice Cream Cake]]\", with the latter becoming the group's breakthrough commercial success. S.M. founder Lee Soo-man served as the EP's [[executive producer]], with [[Hayley Aitken]], Trinity Music, [[Deekay|Daniel \"Obi\" Klein]], [[Charli Taft]], [[Jam Factory]], [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]], [[Teddy Riley]], [[Cha Cha Malone]], MonoTree and others contributed lyrics and production.\n\nUpon its release, ''Ice Cream Cake'' received positive reviews from music critics for its \"impressive effort\" of establishing the two sides of their musical identity. The EP also attained commercial success, becoming Red Velvet's first chart-topper on the [[Gaon Album Chart]] in South Korea and number two on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' World Albums Chart for the first time, while peaking at number twenty-four on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s [[Top Heatseekers|Heatseekers Albums chart]]. It has since sold a cumulative sales of over 88,000 copies, as of September 2018.\n\n==Background and release==\n\n=== Background ===\nFollowing the end of \"Be Natural\" promotion in late October 2014, it was announced that Red Velvet would return with an [[extended play]], marking their first proper release since the group's debut in last August. In February 2015, Red Velvet was spotted filming in a [[desert]] just outside of [[Palmdale, California]] with then [[SM Rookies]]-member [[Yeri (singer)|Yeri]], with the then-rumored song title to be \"Blonde Girl\". Yeri was then introduced by [[S.M. Entertainment]] as the fifth member of Red Velvet through two videos uploaded on the label's [[YouTube]] channel on March 11 and March 12, which contained audio previews of then-unknown album track \"Somethin Kinda Crazy\".<ref>{{cite web |title=[Video] Red Velvet Welcomes New Member Yeri in Time for Comeback |last=Hong |first=Grace Danbi |website=enewsWorld |url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/88938/video-red-velvet-welcomes-new-member-yeri-in-time-for-comeback |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |date=March 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303165837/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/88938/video-red-velvet-welcomes-new-member-yeri-in-time-for-comeback |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On the same day, they revealed the title of the group's first album, ''Ice Cream Cake''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mk.co.kr/news/headline/2015/232805 |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |website=MK News |date=March 11, 2015|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \uc0c8 \uba64\ubc84 '\uc608\ub9ac' \ud569\ub958 5\uc778\uc870 \ubcc0\uc2e0\u202618\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31|language=ko}}</ref> On March 14, the music video for \"Automatic\" was released days prior to the EP's release, with title track \"Ice Cream Cake\" followed suit on March 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20150315n05007 |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |author=Yoon Sang-geun |website=Nate |date=March 15, 2015|title=\ucef4\ubc31 \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \ub354\ube14 \ud0c0\uc774\ud2c0\uace1 \ud65c\ub3d9\u2026\ubba4\ube44 \uae30\uc2b5 \uacf5\uac1c|language=ko}}</ref> SM Entertainment confirmed that the group would be promoting both \"Ice Cream Cake\" and \"Automatic\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.hankooki.com/lpage/entv/201503/sp20150315101948136690.htm |accessdate=March 16, 2015 |author=Lee Jong-hyun |website=Hankooki |date=March 15, 2015|title='\ucef4\ubc31' \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \ubc18\uc804 \ub9e4\ub825 \uc120\uc0ac! 'Automatic' MV \uae30\uc2b5 \uacf5\uac1c|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===Release===\nThe mini-album was released in two versions, ''Ice Cream Cake'' and ''Automatic''. While there are no changes in the track list, the ''Automatic'' version has an alternative cover which features the original artwork in black and white, along with the design of the physical disc and the photo book inside is different from the other version.\n\n== Composition ==\n\n=== Concept ===\nNot only does the group's name \"Red Velvet\" represent their two different images, it also represents the duality sonic concept that the group was focusing on since their debut in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/101320/20140729/sm-entertainments-new-girl-group-red-velvet-finally-unveiled.htm|title=SM Entertainment's New Girl Group \u201cRed Velvet\u201d Finally Unveiled|date=2014-07-29|website=KpopStarz|accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref> While the \"Red\" concept shows the group's \"sweet, bubblegum side\", the \"Velvet\" concept highlights the group as \"sultry sirens\" with \"slow-burning, [[Janet Jackson]]-esque [[R&B]] jam\".<ref name=\":1\" /> ''Ice Cream Cake'' marks the first release from Red Velvet to contain both \"Red\" and \"Velvet\" composition, which was eventually followed by two different releases that focused solely on a single sonic concept: ''[[The Red (album)|The Red]]'' in September 2015 and [[The Velvet|''The Velvet'']] in March 2016. \n\n=== Songs ===\n{{Listen|filename=Ice Cream Cake, song by Red Velvet.ogg|title=\"Ice Cream Cake\"|format=[[Ogg]]|pos=right|description=\"Ice Cream Cake\" is a [[dance-pop]] song with influences of [[bubblegum pop]] and [[drum and bass]]. The song represents the \"Red\" sonic concept of the group.}}The extended play starts with the same-name track \"Ice Cream Cake\", a \"punchy, sugary pop confection\" that consists elements from [[Bubblegum pop|bubblegum-pop]] and [[drum and bass]]. Produced by [[Hayley Aitken]] and producing team Trinity Music, the song original title was \"Ice Cream Truck\" before the lyrics was rewritten in Korean by songwriter Jo Yoon-kyung and Kim Dong-hyun. In addition, it also features \"haunted\" [[harmony]] which can be heard during the intro of the song, while being accompanied by the sound of a [[music box]]. The lyrics tell the excitement of a girl being attracted to her boyfriend, using \"ice cream cake\" as a [[metaphor]] to the girl's feelings. Along with the electro-pop \"Stupid Cupid\" and the bright, poppy \"Take It Slow\", the three tracks represented the \"Red\" concept, with \"Stupid Cupid\" offers a different \"aura\" through the electric riffs, and \"Take It Slow\" highlights the group's harmonization and soft vocals that recalls \"the perfection\" from fellow labelmate [[Girls' Generation-TTS]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://izm.co.kr/contentRead.asp?idx=26679&bigcateidx=1&subcateidx=3&view_tp=1&view_sort=1|title=Neo Music Communication IZM|website=izm.co.kr |url-status=live |accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref>{{Listen|filename=Automatic (song sample).ogg|title=\"Automatic\"|format=[[Ogg]]|pos=right|description=\"Automatic\" is a [[contemporary R&B]] song with influence from [[neo soul]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://izm.co.kr/contentRead.asp?idx=26679&bigcateidx=1&subcateidx=3&view_tp=1&view_sort=1|first=Do-hyun|last=Kim|title=Ice Cream Cake - 2015 - Red Velvet|website=izm.co.kr|publisher=IZM |url-status=live ||accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref> The song represents the \"Velvet\" sonic concept of the group.}}On the other hand, the second track \"Automatic\" is \"a surely implemented R&B track\" with influence from neo soul, thus represents the \"Velvet\" sonic concept. Produced by [[Deekay|Daniel \"Obi\" Klein]] and British singer-songwriter [[Charli Taft]], the song marks the first work from the duo with Red Velvet and they would later participate in the group's upcoming releases. Lyrically, the song tells how \"natural\" and \"automatic\" the senses and feelings of a girl come just by the touch of her lover, with the opening monologue \"How do you like this beat?/Natural and automatic for you.\" Charli Taft also co-produced the third track \"Something Kinda Crazy\", a modern-R&B track with synth-pop influence that sings about the starstruck feelings of a girl when she falls in a relationship. The lyrics was written by songwriter [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]], with [[American]] [[Record producer|producer]] [[Teddy Riley]] joined in the production. The closing track \"Candy\" is a \"smoothing, popping\" R&B track that sings about the wishes of a long-lasting relationship. \n\n== Promotion ==\nSM Entertainment announced a program where in the group will be promoting their new album, called ''Ice Cream TV''. The group performed the songs live in the show, which was streamed through [[Naver Corporation|Naver Music]] and was hosted by [[Shinee]]'s [[Choi Minho (singer)|Minho]]. Besides their live performances, the group also talked about the new album and their 'comeback'.<ref name=\"Mwave1\" />\n\nThe group started promoting their singles \"Automatic\" and \"Ice Cream Cake\" on music shows on March 19. They first performed the songs on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s ''[[M Countdown]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/89732/redvelvet-interview|title=[Interview] Red Velvet Talks Rumors Surrounding Member Change, Goals for 'Ice Cream Cake' and More|last=Jeon|first=Ah Ram|date=March 22, 2015|website=Newsen|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303191753/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/89732/redvelvet-interview|archive-date=March 3, 2016|accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> followed by performances on [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]' ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' on March 20<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2015/03/20/super-junior-des-growing-pains-wins-on-music-bank/|title=Super Junior D&E's \"Growing Pains\" Wins on Music Bank|date=March 20, 2015|website=Soompi|accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> and [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]' ''[[Inkigayo]]'' on March 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/474549|title='\uc778\uae30\uac00\uc694' \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \uc804\ud600 \ub2e4\ub978 \ub450 \uac00\uc9c0 \ub9e4\ub825 '\uc544\uc774\uc2a4\ud06c\ub9bc \ucf00\uc774\ud06c'\uc640 '\uc624\ud1a0\ub9e4\ud2f1'|author=Hwang Seong-un|date=March 22, 2015|website=10asia|language=ko|accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> They returned to ''Music Bank'' a week later and won their first music show trophy since their official debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreadaily.com/news/read.asp?page=1&branch=NEWS&source=&category=entertainment&art_id=3265626|title='\ubba4\ubc45' \ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \ub370\ubdd4 7\uac1c\uc6d4\ub9cc \uac00\uc694\ud504\ub85c \uccab 1\uc704..\ub208\ubb3c \ud391\ud391|author=Kim Mi-hwa|date=March 27, 2015|website=Korea Daily|language=ko|accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref> They had their first overseas performance of \"Ice Cream Cake\" and their first as a 5-member group in an [[SM Town]] concert held in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/474384|title=SMTOWN, \ub300\ub9cc \ud640\ub838\ub2e4\u2026SMTOWN LIVE \ub300\ub9cc \uacf5\uc5f0 \uc131\uacf5\ub9ac\uc5d0 \ub9c8\ubb34\ub9ac|author=Hwang Seong-un|date=March 22, 2015|website=10asia|language=ko|accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> The group has also promoted and performed songs from the album in the Philippines for the ''Best of the Best K-pop Concert'' on April 12, a concert which also featured labelmates [[Super Junior]] and [[Girls' Generation]] as well as [[Cube Entertainment|Cube]] boy band [[BTOB]].\nThe group also had its first promotions in the United States at KCON on August 2 at the Staples Center in [[downtown]] [[Los Angeles]]. The group participated in a fan engagement session at the [[Los Angeles Convention Center]] and performed songs \"Ice Cream Cake\", \"Somethin' Kinda Crazy\", and \"Happiness\" during the concert.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[IZM]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://izm.co.kr/contentRead.asp?idx=26679&bigcateidx=1&subcateidx=3&view_tp=1&view_sort=1 |website=IZM|author=Kim Do-hyun|publisher=IZM|title=Ice Cream Cake|language=korean |url-status=live |accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3.5|5}}\n| rev1score = \n| rev2 = ''Seoulbeats''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://seoulbeats.com/2015/03/sweet-love-red-velvets-ice-cream-cake/ |website=Seoulbeats|author=Chelsea|publisher=Seoulbeats|title=Ice Cream Cake|language=English |url-status=live |accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n| rev2score = {{rating|3.75|5}}\n}}Upon its initial release, ''Ice Cream Cake'' received positive reviews from most music critics for showcasing the duality sonic concept of the group. Jakob Dorof of pop music magazine ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' described the track \"Ice Cream Cake\" as \"a treat as unexpected as it is unpredictable [...] packs a punch, but goes down smooth over time\" and deemed it \"the SM label's specialty: bubblegum pop that deeply rewards repeat rotations.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dorof|first1=Jakob|title=SPIN K-Pop Report: Ga-In Subverts Adam & Eve, Lim Kim Pops Smoky Bubblegum|url=http://www.spin.com/2015/06/spin-k-pop-report-ga-in-subverts-adam-eve-lim-kim-pops-smoky-bubblegum/|website=Spin|publisher=SpinMedia|accessdate=30 September 2015|date=2015-06-11}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'<nowiki/>''s Jeff Benjamin called the album \"an impressive effort for such a young group\" and praised its ability to personify the group's dual-sided musical identity through the singles \"Ice Cream Cake\" and \"Automatic.\" He explained: \"The former track is a punchy, sugary pop confection that [...] seems to represent the outfit's sweet bubblegum side; their \"Red\" side if you will. While the latter is a slow-burning, Janet Jackson-esque R&B jam that [...] positions them as sultry sirens; their \"Velvet\" side.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|last1=Benjamin|first1=Jeff|title=Red Velvet Send Delicious 'Ice Cream' EP to World, Heatseeker Albums Charts|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6516563/red-velvet-ice-cream-cake-automatic-ep|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref> In a positive review for the EP, writer Kim Do-hyun of ''IZM'' complemented the strong R&B influence in the release, while noting that the release is \"an independent statement\" for the group, choosing the two singles, \"Something Kinda Crazy\" and \"Take It Slow\" to be the highlights of the EP.<ref name=\":2\" /> Another review from ''Seoulbeats'' described the EP as \"an earnestly sweet album that shows the wide range of talent the ladies of Red Velvet possess.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seoulbeats.com/2015/03/sweet-love-red-velvets-ice-cream-cake/|title=Sweet Love in Red Velvet\u2019s \u201cIce Cream Cake\u201d|date=2015-03-28|website=Seoulbeats|language=en-US |url-status=live |accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref> The two singles would later appear in the top 25 Red Velvet songs by ''Billboard'', with \"Automatic\" at number nine and \"Ice Cream Cake\" at number eighteen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8525588/best-red-velvet-songs-critics-picks|title=Red Velvet's 25 Best Songs|date=2019-07-31|website=Billboard|accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nOn the week of March 15, 2015, ''Ice Cream Cake'' debuted and spent one week at number one on the weekly [[Gaon Album Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.news.nate.com/view/20150326n25639 |accessdate=March 26, 2015 |website=Nate |date=March 26, 2015 |title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \uac00\uc628 \uc8fc\uac04 \uc568\ubc94\ucc28\ud2b8\ub3c4 1\uc704 '\uc815\uc0c1 \ud589\uc9c4'|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=13&hitYear=2015&termGbn=week|title=Gaon Weekly Album Chart - Week 13, 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=gaonchart.co.kr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref> giving the group their first chart-topping title. All six songs from the album eventually charted in the same week on Gaon Singles Chart.<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150326020637/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=ALL&targetTime=13&hitYear=2015&termGbn=week South Korea's] [[Gaon Singles Chart]]<span> from March 15\u201321, 2015 (in Korean)</span> Originally from [[Gaon Music Chart]] (March 2015). Archived March 26, 2015. Retrieved March 26, 2015.</ref> The album went on to become the best selling album by a girl group in South Korea on the Hanteo Chart for the first half of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreadaily.com/news/read.asp?art_id=3470045|title=\uc0c1\ubc18\uae30 \uc74c\ubc18\ud310\ub9e4, \uc5d1\uc18c 1~3\uc704 \uc11d\uad8c..\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \u5973\uc720\uc77c \ud1b120|author=Gil Hye-seong|date=June 21, 2015|website=Korea Daily|language=ko|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref> With a total of 48,815 copies sold in 2015, the extended play was the 50th best-selling release on the 2015's Gaon Year-End Album Chart, and later achieved a cumulative sales of over 88,000 copies as of September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=2015&hitYear=2015&termGbn=year|title=2015's Gaon Year-End Album Chart|last=|first=|date=|website=gaonchart.co.kr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-04-29}}</ref> It also debuted at number two on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s World Albums Chart, becoming their first charting entry.<ref name=\"BillboardWAC\">{{cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2015032708333431217&outlink=2&SVEC |accessdate=March 27, 2015 |author=Yoon Seong-yeol |website=Star News |date=March 27, 2015|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, \u7f8e\ube4c\ubcf4\ub4dc \uc6d4\ub4dc\uc568\ubc94 2\uc704 \uc9c4\uc785..MFBTY 8\uc704|language=ko}}</ref> The album also peaked at 25 on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s [[Top Heatseekers]] on April 4, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/heatseekers-albums/2015-04-04|title=Heatseekers Albums: Up and Coming Musicians Chart}}</ref> The album is also the group's first appearance on the Japan's [[Oricon Albums Chart]], peaking at number 76 for one week. \n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing =\n| all_lyrics =\n| all_music =\n| collapsed = no\n| headline =\n| extra_column = Arrangement\n| title1 = [[Ice Cream Cake (Red Velvet song)|Ice Cream Cake]]\n| length1 = 3:11\n| lyrics1 = Jo Yoon-kyung, Kim Dong-hyun\n| music1 = [[Hayley Aitken]], Sebastian Lundberg, Fredrik Haggstam, Johan Gustafson a.k.a. Trinity Music\n| extra1 = Hayley Aitken, Sebastian Lundberg, Fredrik Haggstam, Johan Gustafson a.k.a. Trinity Music\n| title2 = [[Automatic (Red Velvet song)|Automatic]]\n| length2 = 3:30\n| lyrics2 = Choi So-young ([[Jam Factory]])\n| music2 = [[Deekay|Daniel \"Obi\" Klein]], [[Charli Taft]]\n| extra2 = Daniel \"Obi\" Klein, Charli Taft\n| title3 = Somethin Kinda Crazy\n| length3 = 3:19\n| lyrics3 = [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]]\n| music3 = Kenzie, Teddy Riley, DOM, Lee Hyun-